<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-06T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-06T17:00:00-05:00" n="1023" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1023">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">822.51/882: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Long</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-06T17:00:00-05:00">June 6, 1940—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 9:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>90. The Provisional President last night expressed appreciation of our
                            Government’s confidence in his administration as evidenced by
                            export-import credit.</p>
                        <p>Dr. Cordova and the Minister for Defense<note n="62" xml:id="d1023fn1">Galo Plaza.</note> believe that the highway construction work ought
                            to be done by a responsible foreign preferably American company with
                            most positions given to Ecuadorans and Ecuadoran engineers
                            cooperating.</p>
                        <p>Despatch by air mail.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>